On Friday, July 22, 2011, Sharon Aagaard and Stan Wood were joined by 7 other birders at their monthly walk for Eastside Audubon at Lake Sammamish State Park in Issaquah WA. The morning was sunny and warm with temps in the mid 50's to high 60's, with very light wind.....perfect birding weather.  We expected it to be a very quiet, non-birdy July morning, but the birds surprised us!  Many were flying about and/or perched up and singing.  We saw and heard many of the usual suspects for this time of year, like a family of Warbling Vireos, a pair of Cedar Waxwings building a nest, a Spotted Sandpiper on Issaquah Creek, a juvenile Bald Eagle perched on a snag overlooking the lake, a pair of Belted Kingfishers flying quietly up the creek, a juvenile Red-breasted Sapsucker preening on a branch in the shade, several Willow Flycatchers still fitz bewing, about a dozen Swainson's Thrushes still singing in the bushes, several singing Yellow Warblers and Common Yellowthroats, one quiet, male Black-headed Grosbeak, and a family of Bullock's Orioles.  For me, the best bird species of the day was seeing 4 Black Swifts fly overhead about 80 feet up in the bright blue, sunny sky.  It was a good morning with delightful, enthusiastic birders, with 48 species seen/heard for the day.

SPECIES COMMENTS: 5 in glasses at one time probably at least 8:  another flock (5-8) of black swifts this morning at Marymount dog park/audubon trail.  Nice place.  Low lying, lots of bugs.  a couple hundred swallows (tree, violet-green and barn) as well as a couple of Vaux's swifts.  Fun to see the difference in flight and size, etc., of the black swifts -  I first noticed they had a tail, they used it, even fanned it out, and they were so lazy compared to all the scurrying swallows and flitting Vaux's - and almost looked hulking like their shoulders were hunched up and wings held a little down and curved.  I don't know why I find them so fascinating, but it's wonderful to see so many of them.  They came from the east, moved west to mix with the main swallow foraging activity  and then leisurely circled/foraged off to the east again and left
Good view compared to Vaux's Swifts

Nineteen intrepid birders sloshed together in the drizzle and mud this morning at Lake Sammamish State Park in Issaquah, WA on a monthly bird walk offered by Eastside Audubon.  It was a cloudy, drippy morning, temps in the low to mid 50's, with winds about 5 mph.  Highlights included seeing a Common Merganser female fly through the trees and land high up on a large Cottonwood branch, then 3 more in with the Canada Geese at the lake's edge, then later, we later saw another female with 4 young nestled underneath her on a large log near the mouth of Issaquah Creek (soon they all woke up, stretched, preened and all 5 scurried out towards the lake).  Some of us saw a GREEN HERON catching a fish in the small pond to the south in the large parking lot on the left of the main entrance (exactly where Amy Schillinger suggested Blair look for it).  While enjoying the behavior of 3 SPOTTED SANDPIPERS feeding along the edge of the point at the mouth of Issaquah Creek, we watched an American Crow disappear at the base of a small tree near the water, fly out with a small, whitish egg in its bill, all the while with the alarmed Sandpipers trying in vain to draw it away from the nest.  Three BLACK SWIFTS foraged low overhead, along with a couple of Vaux's Swifts.  The RED-BREASTED SAPSUCKER parents continue to feed their young in the tree snag nest discovered about two weeks ago (on the south edge of the Sunset Beach parking lot).  The Band-Tailed Pigeon nest nearby appeared to be empty.  One (maybe two?) RED-EYED VIREO was heard singing, along with several Warbling Vireos in the large Cottonwood forest at the south end.  We also heard a couple of YELLOW-RUMPED WARBLERS singing near the same forest.  In two areas, we could hear and then got great looks at several BULLOCK'S ORIOLES but could not locate their nests.  54 species were seen/heard for the day, with a total of 110 for the year.

Just me out for a walk and to see who's there.  Parked in the large lot on the left and walked along the south boarder of Sunset Beach parking lot to access the trail in the SE corner to bird just the cottonwood forest.

It was a thrill to pull into Lake Sam's parking lot and see at least 8 BLACK SWIFTS, several VAUX'S SWIFTS and swallows bug catching directly overhead!  Sharon Aagaard and Stan Wood birded with 20 others at Eastside Audubon's monthly bird walk at Lake Sammamish State Park on June 11, 2013, from 8 am to noon. Weather-wise, it was mostly sunny with partial clouds, 10-12 mph winds and temps in the mid to high 50s. HIGHLIGHTS: 2 of the 3 escaped SWAN GEESE are still there; 1 male CINNAMON TEAL was hanging with the Mallards on the sandy bank (thanks Ollie!); 1 OSPREY; 1 COOPER'S HAWK; 4 BALD EAGLES of various ages; at least 4 SPOTTED SANDPIPERS; at least 12 BAND-TAILED PIGEONS; 8 BLACK SWIFT; 4 VAUX'S SWIFT; 1 ANNA'S HUMMINGBIRD; 4 RUFOUS HUMMINGBIRDS; 2 BELTED KINGFISHERS; 4 RED-BREASTED SAPSUCKERS; 8 WESTERN WOOD-PEWEES; 10 WILLOW FLYCATCHERS; 1 PACIFIC-SLOPE FLYCACTHER; 8 WARBLING VIREOS; a 5 SWALLOW morning (no Bank); 20 SWAINSON'S THRUSHES; 8 BLACK-HEADED GROSBEAKS; 1 LAZULI BUNTING (thanks Sara!); 6 BULLOCK'S ORIOLES; and 4 PURPLE FINCHES. 53 species for the day; 105 for the year. The next bird walk is JULY 23. No pre-registration, just show up depending on your mood or the weather. Since this is a state park, a Discover Pass is necessary to park ($10 daily, $30 annual). We meet in the large parking lot to the left just inside the main park entrance (not the boat launch entrance).

Sharon Aagaard and Stan Wood birded with 7 others at Eastside Audubon's monthly bird walk at Lake Sammamish State Park on August 13, 2014, from 8:00 am to 11:50 am. TRIP COMMENTS: - met up with Jordan at 6:45 and did a ~7 mile foray through the park with some overlap in walking.  Cloudy at first with occasional light drizzle and high fog.  Eventually lifted for a mostly sunny day with a light north breeze picking up later.  No luck with shorebirds on beach below Daybreak Star today.  Unfortunately the cool temps (esp. w/ breeze at W pt) and extensive walking on rocks caused IT band syndrome to be noticeable at the end of the day.--- Jordan spotted a young opossum just s of wolf tree woods area and near Daybreak Star we saw a fairly large box-like turtle on the trail (update: looks like a Three-toed Box Turtle, which would have to be someone's released pet).
SPECIES COMMENTS: flew low over chapel about 7, just after sunrise.  Jordan and I both called out BLSW simultaneously.  It was obviously a large dark swift, with long wings and long tail, proportionally larger than VASW with much "steadier" flight style.  Conditions were perfect for BLSW at the time with low clouds.  I wonder where, if anywhere, it had roosted the previous night?  First for the park for Evan, and first Sept. record anywhere in WA.

LOCALITY: Bear Creek Bird Survey for EAS, Redmond WA
TRIP COMMENTS: Sharon Aagaard performed this monthly bird census on behalf of Eastside Audubon on May 24, 2015. It was cloudy, 54F, 0-1 mph. Mammals:  just 2 bunnies.  No trucks and workers were present. Appears all potted plants have now been planted. With the exception of Mallard, Canada Goose, Killdeer and a flyover Belted Kingfisher, the creek and nearby edges had no other species at this time. Survey area is just south of Redmond Towne Center--from NE 76th St/Redmond Way&520 to Leary Way). Three areas within a 3/4 mile section of Bear Creek were surveyed.: Area 1--from Redmond Way walking west along the trail which parallels the meandering creek to where it straightens out; Area 2--continuing on the trail along the now straight creek to the 3 ponds; and Area 3--the 3 ponds, field and the coniferous forest next to Leary Way. Sharon, Nancy and Jo performed this month's bird census.  Sharon arrived at 04:44 am, ahead of the 5:30 am start, to look for owls at the blueberry farm.  Nancy and Jo arrived a little while later.  We had no success seeing owls this month.  In addition to birds, two bats were seen around 5 am; 3 Bunnies; and a few turtles.  From 5:30 to 8:15 am, the three of us surveyed the section north of the P&R lot. It was cloudy, 62-70F, 0-2 mph. The route we followed began at the unpaved trail located at the east corner of the south parking lot at the South Bellevue P&R lot. Then north along the trail bordering the blueberry fields, to the NE corner of same, returning back to the footbridge crossing over the Mercer Slough, walking east on an unpaved trail to 118th Ave SE. Then north to the Pacific Science Center, using the lookouts overlooking the wetlands, then returning on an unpaved trail heading south through the woods to reconnect with the trail heading back down into the Slough. At the bottom of this trail, then north across a creek to walk a loop and returning back to the footbridge across the Slough and then back to the parking lot on the same trail we used at the beginning. From 8:15 to 9:21 am, we surveyed the section south of the P&R lot. Continuing cloudy skies, 70-71F, 5-8 mph. We walked south from the parking lot on a paved biking/walking trail, crossing underneath I90 to view a small cove/marina on Lake Washington. Then, returning back the way we came, making a short stop at the top of the biking/walking bridge high over the southernmost end of the Slough. We ended the census here and returned back to the parking lot (noting only new species not seen earlier in this area). Submitted from BirdLog NA for Android v1.96.
SPECIES COMMENTS: perfect low cloud conditions, seen from the road as we left the Science Center..... flying high near each other, directly overhead, moslty gliding with very little wing flapping, no twisting, had long wings, notched, flaired tails, black in color

Sharon Aagaard and Stan Wood birded with 16 others at Eastside Audubon's monthly bird walk at Lake Sammamish State Park on July 22, 2015, from 8:00 am to about noon. Skies were mostly cloudy, 63-69F, 3-9 mph.   HIGHLIGHTS: 1 adult GREEN HERON was perched and preening on a horizontal tree stump in Issaquah Creek; 1 ACCIPITER SP., most likely a Cooper's Hawk; 4 SPOTTED SANDPIPERS, in 3 different areas, 3 juv and 1 adult; 2 LEAST SANDPIPERS at the mouth of Issaquah Creek; 1 RING-BILLED GULL; 2 BAND-TAILED PIGEONS, 1 BLACK SWIFT; 1 immat. RED-BREASTED SAPSUCKER; 1 PILEATED WOODPECKER heard; 4 WESTERN WOOD-PEWEES; 8 WILLOW FLYCATCHERS; 2 singing PACIFIC-SLOPE FLYCATCHERS, one bird frantically being pursued by and feeding two Brown-headed Cowbirds; 2 WARBLING VIREOS; 8 SWAINSON'S THRUSHES; 4 warbler species: COMMON YELLOWTHROAT, YELLOW WARBLER, YELLOW-RUMPED WARBLER, and WILSON'S WARBLER. 4 WESTERN TANAGERS; 4 BLACK-HEADED GROSBEAKS; and 3 BULLOCK'S ORIOLES.  53 species for the day, 126 for the year. Critters: 5 deer, including one female with two fawns; Eastern Gray Squirrels and bunnies. We left the park wondering "Did a few of us hear a Yellow-breasted Chat call 3 times near the orchard??"  We did not get a response to brief play back, so it's a mention only and is not officially listed in this eBird report.  The next bird walk is Monday, AUGUST 17. No pre-registration, just show up depending on your mood or the weather. Since this is a state park, a Discover Pass is necessary to park ($10 daily, $30 annual). We meet in the large parking lot to the left just inside the main park entrance, now signed as the Costco Parking lot, but we meet at the far end towards the lake (not the boat launch entrance).Submitted from BirdLog NA for Android v1.96.
SPECIES COMMENTS: flew over the parking lot, early at the beginning of the walk

RED-BREASTED SAPSUCKER; 1 PILEATED WOODPECKER heard; 4 WESTERN WOOD-PEWEES; 8 WILLOW FLYCATCHERS; 2 singing PACIFIC-SLOPE FLYCATCHERS, one bird frantically being pursued by and feeding two Brown-headed Cowbirds; 2 WARBLING VIREOS; 8 SWAINSON'S THRUSHES; 4 warbler species: COMMON YELLOWTHROAT, YELLOW WARBLER, YELLOW-RUMPED WARBLER, and WILSON'S WARBLER. 4 WESTERN TANAGERS; 4 BLACK-HEADED GROSBEAKS; and 3 BULLOCK'S ORIOLES.  53 species for the day, 126 for the year. Critters: 5 deer, including one female with two fawns; Eastern Gray Squirrels and bunnies. We left the park wondering "Did a few of us hear a Yellow-breasted Chat call 3 times near the orchard??"  We did not get a response to brief play back, so it's a mention only and is not officially listed in this eBird report.  The next bird walk is Monday, AUGUST 17. No pre-registration, just show up depending on your mood or the weather. Since this is a state park, a Discover Pass is necessary to park ($10 daily, $30 annual). We meet in the large parking lot to the left just inside the main park entrance, now signed as the Costco Parking lot, but we meet at the far end towards the lake (not the boat launch entrance).Submitted from BirdLog NA for Android v1.96.

Sharon, Nancy and Jo performed this month's bird census.  Sharon arrived at 04:44 am, ahead of the 5:30 am start, to look for owls at the blueberry farm.  Nancy and Jo arrived a little while later.  We had no success seeing owls this month.  In addition to birds, two bats were seen around 5 am; 3 Bunnies; and a few turtles.  From 5:30 to 8:15 am, the three of us surveyed the section north of the P&R lot. It was cloudy, 62-70F, 0-2 mph. The route we followed began at the unpaved trail located at the east corner of the south parking lot at the South Bellevue P&R lot. Then north along the trail bordering the blueberry fields, to the NE corner of same, returning back to the footbridge crossing over the Mercer Slough, walking east on an unpaved trail to 118th Ave SE. Then north to the Pacific Science Center, using the lookouts overlooking the wetlands, then returning on an unpaved trail heading south through the woods to reconnect with the trail heading back down into the Slough. At the bottom of this trail, then north across a creek to walk a loop and returning back to the footbridge across the Slough and then back to the parking lot on the same trail we used at the beginning. From 8:15 to 9:21 am, we surveyed the section south of the P&R lot. Continuing cloudy skies, 70-71F, 5-8 mph. We walked south from the parking lot on a paved biking/walking trail, crossing underneath I90 to view a small cove/marina on Lake Washington. Then, returning back the way we came, making a short stop at the top of the biking/walking bridge high over the southernmost end of the Slough. We ended the census here and returned back to the parking lot (noting only new species not seen earlier in this area). Submitted from BirdLog NA for Android v1.96.
SPECIES COMMENTS: perfect low cloud conditions, seen from the road as we left the Science Center..... flying high near each other, directly overhead, moslty gliding with very little wing flapping, no twisting, had long wings, notched, flaired tails, black in color

TRIP COMMENTS: Much worse morning weather than forecast for my Windy Gap campout, with morning cloud bank, mist, and wind limiting ridge-top views and bird activity. Early morning birding in the protected drainage on the north side of the ridge was extremely productive. Impressive numbers of birds, including a distracting overabundance of robins and juncos, made for an enjoyable morning despite the wet and cold. With increasing late-morning cloud breaks a return closer to the ridge tops yielded some raptors - including some exciting falcon watching - though car trouble cut my day a bit short. Also seen: one large bull elk, one pika, one rabbit, and an assortment of ground squirrels.----I did finally manage to get my car home, but unfortunately in my fluster managed to leave my camera behind at the intersection where NF-195 heads southwest and briefly follows the ridge/county line (before dropping south into Kittitas county to skirt a small peak) and the road I can't find a number for that wraps around the drainage on the north side of the ridge. My car is out of commission for a while, so I've decided this might be an excuse to get a better birding camera. However... if you happen to go in the next few days and find a Panasonic Lumix camera, please contact me through my Flickr account - I'd love to get it back! --
SPECIES COMMENTS: Passed low over the ridge while foraging - light barring on belly visible.

LOCALITY: Bear Creek Bird Survey for EAS, Redmond WA
TRIP COMMENTS:
Sharon Aagaard performed this monthly bird census on behalf of Eastside Audubon on July 30, 2016. Cloudy, 62-65F, 7-9 mph. It felt much like a fall morning. As expected, creek water level is just below the lowest stacked logs on the banks, flowing slowly. The area where I can see rough/white water flowing over rocks is still rough, but less so. Grasses are dry, and many of the plantings are surviving (Cedars, Doug Firs, Maples, Willows), but many have died. Other than blackberry bushes providing berries for the birds and other critters, I wonder if cascara bark plants were put in? I didn't see any. They provide abundant berries this time of year (LSSP has lots). SE pond was 80-90% full of thick vegetation, with just a couple small open water channels. The other 3 ponds have 50% open water. Life in or on the edges of the Creek: Canada Geese. Mammals: several bunnies were seen today. The survey area is just south of Redmond Towne Center--from NE 76th St/Redmond Way&520 to Leary Way). Three areas within a 3/4 mile section of Bear Creek were surveyed.: Area 1--from Redmond Way walking west along the trail which parallels the meandering creek to where it straightens out; Area 2--continuing on the trail along the now straight creek to the 3 ponds; and Area 3--the 3 ponds, field and the coniferous forest next to Leary Way.
Submitted from eBird Android 1.2.3
